The Diana Davis Spencer Foundation Grands Teach For America – D.C. Region $3 Million to Enhance Local Education Efforts











      Body    



WASHINGTON, D.C., May 25, 2016—The Diana Davis Spencer Foundation granted Teach For America–D.C. Region $3 million, to be distributed over three years, to expand recruitment and ongoing professional support of current corps members and alumni working in the area’s low-income schools.
This comes as the region prioritizes building on its history of providing culturally responsive corps members and alumni teachers by developing their leadership and enduring commitment as education advocates locally and nationally. With grants like these, the region is able to provide teachers with the necessary tools and skills to create affirming and culturally relevant pedagogy for their students. By engaging in this professional development, current corps members Tihitina Chamiso (D.C. Region Corps ’15) and Deseree King (D.C. Region Corps ’15) were able to lead their first grade students to complete “Where I'm From" projects which focused on strengthening their students’ senses of self and cultural pride.
“I am grateful to the Diana Davis Spencer Foundation and excited that their contribution will allow our current teachers and alumni to continue working with local teachers, principals, and partnering districts to keep making a positive difference for students and families,” said Teach For America–D.C. Region executive director Adele Fabrikant. “It is through commitment like this that we can recruit, train, and empower talented and diverse leaders to expand educational opportunity for students in our community.”
Since 1992, Teach For America–D.C.  Region has collaborated with local public and charter schools to attract, retain, and support 3,500 effective educators who have impacted 224,000 students across the region. These educators have worked in collaboration with school leaders and students across the district as part of the effort to ensure D.C. Public Schools’ National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP) scores continue to improve. Last year’s high scores led to D.C. becoming the fastest improving urban school district in the nation. Of 2,600 TFA alumni currently working in the region, 55 percent remain in education. Ryan Tauriainen (Hawaii Corps’08), for example, was named The Washington Post’s 2016 Principal of the Year for his impact at AppleTree Institute Early Learning Public Charter School. Alumni no longer in the classroom, impact the region in other ways – through graduate school, law, policy, advocacy and business.
“Teach For America corps members and alumni bring their passion, enthusiasm, and innovation to the classroom and with their heart and soul, they help students realize the importance of staying in school,” said Diana Davis Spencer, President of the foundation. “The Diana Davis Spencer Foundation is enthusiastic to support these dedicated corps members and alumni.”
In March, the region honored Spencer at its sixth annual gala, highlighting how grants from her foundation and those like it allow Teach For America–D.C. Region to develop a new strategic approach and innovative methods for corps member retention and alumni engagement, all contributing to expanding opportunities for students across the D.C. area. 








About Teach For America 
Teach For America works in partnership with communities to expand educational opportunity for children facing the challenges of poverty. Founded in 1990, Teach For America recruits and develops a diverse corps of outstanding college graduates and professionals to make an initial two-year commitment to teach in high-need schools and become lifelong leaders in the effort to end educational inequity. Today, 8,600 corps members are teaching in 52 urban and rural regions across the country while more than 42,000 alumni work across sectors to ensure that all children have access to an excellent education. Teach For America is a proud member of the AmeriCorps national service network. For more information, visit www.teachforamerica.org and follow us on Facebook and Twitter. 
 
About the Diana Davis Spencer Foundation
The Diana Davis Spencer Foundation espouses the values upon which our nation was founded: duty, honor, freedom, individual responsibility, and the work ethic. The mission of the Foundation is to promote entrepreneurship, self-reliance, global understanding, free enterprise, and to enhance the quality of life by supporting the arts, education, health advancements, and preservation of the environment.










